## <a id="topic_whatsnew"></a>What's New in Pivotal GemFire <%=vars.product_version%>

Pivotal GemFire <%=vars.product_version%> includes the following improvements:

- New capability to create AsyncEventQueue in a paused state is added. This provides better controlling of event dispatch with AsyncEventQueue. The event dispatching could be paused from the create time and resumed when application is ready for event consumption.

- Add Micrometer meters to measure function executions and cache get operations, as well as JVM metrics related to garbage collection, threads, processors, uptime, and file descriptors. All Micrometer meters will now automatically be tagged with the member type (one of: locator, server, server-locator, embedded-cache). Micrometer metrics is still considered experimental and the API may change in a later release.

- Here is the api docs for Geode 1.10 cluster management service: https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/GEODE/1.10.0+Management+REST+API+-+experimental
Here is the api docs for Geode 1.11 cluster management service: https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/GEODE/1.11.0+Management+REST+API+-+v1
These are the 3 major changes:
    1. to reduce the future migration cost, update url end point from /management/experimental to /management/v1, but Cluster Management Service is still considered experimental and the API may change in a later release.
    2. simplify the configuration data model, you can configure object in a simple way
    3. add "links" part to every response,  to support HATEOAS

## Pivotal GemFire <%=vars.product_version%> Breaking Change

**GEODE 5861:**
The configuration options for JNDI bindings have changed,
whether configured through XML or `gfsh create jndi-binding`:

- The `--jdbc-driver-class` option is now optional.
- `--url` is an alias for the `--connnection-url` option.
- The `--type` option now defaults to `SIMPLE`.
- The `--type=POOLED` option defaults to creating a Hikari pool.
Or, implement `org.apache.geode.datasource.PooledDataSourceFactory`
to customize the class that implements the pool.

The breaking change represents a rare use case.
The change is that
a custom class that implements the pool must now implement the
`org.apache.geode.datasource.PooledDataSourceFactory` interface.

